    "review::.::holistic::abstraction_fitness::docker_listener_no_shutdown_contract::ec53c4af": {
      "id": "review::.::holistic::abstraction_fitness::docker_listener_no_shutdown_contract::ec53c4af",
      "detector": "review",
      "file": ".",
      "tier": 3,
      "confidence": "high",
      "summary": "Docker event listener/subscriber routines have no explicit stop contract, so background lifecycle control is pushed into global goroutine orchestration rather than the abstraction interface.",
      "detail": {
        "holistic": true,
        "dimension": "abstraction_fitness",
        "related_files": [
          "goseg/routines/docker.go",
          "goseg/main.go",
          "goseg/routines/version.go"
        ],
        "evidence": [
          "`DockerListener` creates `ctx := context.Background()` and calls `cli.Events(ctx, ...)` while `main.go` launches it as a fire-and-forget goroutine (`go routines.DockerListener()`) with no cancellable handle.",
          "The function loops forever on `select { case event := <-messages; case err := <-errs }` with no `ctx.Done()` or close-channel handling, so callers cannot express graceful stop/restart boundaries.",
          "Other background subsystems in the same code path (for example `CheckVersionLoop` and `startServer` flow) are also goroutine-spawned without shared lifecycle wiring, increasing subsystem coupling."
        ],
        "suggestion": "Refactor `DockerListener` to accept a runtime context and/or stop channel in its constructor/runtime struct; have `main` own a cancellation scope and close it on shutdown paths so tests and orchestrators can deterministically stop/restart listener loops.",
        "reasoning": ""
      },
      "status": "auto_resolved",
      "note": "Disappeared from scan \u2014 likely fixed",
      "first_seen": "2026-03-01T18:19:05+00:00",
      "last_seen": "2026-03-01T18:19:05+00:00",
      "resolved_at": "2026-03-01T18:48:31+00:00",
      "reopen_count": 0,
      "lang": "go",
