    "review::.::holistic::design_coherence::STRINGLY_TYPED-WORKFLOW-CONTROL::216f1144": {
      "id": "review::.::holistic::design_coherence::STRINGLY_TYPED-WORKFLOW-CONTROL::216f1144",
      "detector": "review",
      "file": ".",
      "tier": 3,
      "confidence": "high",
      "summary": "Multiple modules rely on stringly-typed workflow/control signals and error text matching instead of typed outcomes.",
      "detail": {
        "holistic": true,
        "dimension": "design_coherence",
        "related_files": [
          "goseg/importer/importer.go",
          "goseg/leak/handler.go",
          "goseg/shipworkflow/startram.go",
          "goseg/routines/docker.go"
        ],
        "evidence": [
          "`runImportUploadPipeline` classifies failure behavior via `strings.HasPrefix(err.Error(), \"Failed to configure imported pier\")`, creating behavior coupling to exact message text.",
          "`processAction` branches on payload `Type` using raw strings (`\"login\"`, `\"logout\"`, `\"password\"`), while other modules publish string statuses/events instead of typed constants/enums.",
          "Container and state transitions in `shipworkflow`/`routines` are also driven by raw status/action/event strings spread across different files."
        ],
        "suggestion": "Introduce shared typed enums/events for operation states and action outcomes (e.g., `ImportPhase`, `LeakAction`, `ShipLifecycleEvent`, `TransitionResult`) and replace string parsing/switching with explicit status/result types.",
        "reasoning": ""
      },
      "status": "open",
      "note": null,
      "first_seen": "2026-03-01T18:49:27+00:00",
      "last_seen": "2026-03-01T18:49:27+00:00",
      "resolved_at": null,
      "reopen_count": 0,
      "lang": "go",
      "suppressed": false,
      "suppressed_at": null,
      "suppression_pattern": null
    },
    "review::.::holistic::design_coherence::BUGREPORT-PATH-BASE-INCONSISTENCY::d8da355a": {
      "id": "review::.::holistic::design_coherence::BUGREPORT-PATH-BASE-INCONSISTENCY::d8da355a",
      "detector": "review",
      "file": ".",
      "tier": 3,
      "confidence": "high",
      "summary": "Bug-report artifact path construction is inconsistent and can bypass configured base path resolution.",
      "detail": {
        "holistic": true,
        "dimension": "design_coherence",
        "related_files": [
          "goseg/handler/system/support.go",
          "goseg/config/config.go",
          "goseg/logger/logger.go"
        ],
        "evidence": [
          "Fallback path logic in `makeBugReportPath` returns `filepath.Join(config.BasePath, \"/bug-reports/\")`, where `\"/bug-reports/\"` is treated as absolute and drops `config.BasePath`.",
          "Elsewhere in the same codebase, base-path assembly is performed differently (relative join/concatenation), so support artifacts and logs can diverge by filesystem root.",
          "This makes artifact location policy less predictable and increases deployment-specific behavior risk."
        ],
        "suggestion": "Normalize path-building through one utility (or config-backed policy) that always treats suffix segments as relative, and centralize artifact-root selection so support, logs, and exports follow one rule.",
        "reasoning": ""
      },
      "status": "fixed",
      "note": "Normalized bug-report artifact pathing to use shared config storage policy and removed absolute-path join bypasses. Also aligned log path handling with the same policy in logger.",
      "first_seen": "2026-03-01T18:49:27+00:00",
      "last_seen": "2026-03-01T18:49:27+00:00",
      "resolved_at": "2026-03-01T18:52:21+00:00",
      "reopen_count": 0,
      "lang": "go",
      "suppressed": false,
      "suppressed_at": null,
      "suppression_pattern": null,
      "resolution_attestation": {
        "kind": "manual",
        "text": "I have actually centralized bug report path construction onto config.GetStoragePath(\"bug-reports\") and removed the local '/bug-reports/' absolute-join logic in handler/system/support.go. I also updated logger.MakeLogPath to use config.GetStoragePath(\"logs\") in goseg/logger/logger.go and added a 'bug-reports' storage route in goseg/config/config.go, so artifact roots follow one policy. I am not gaming the score by resolving without fixing.",
        "attested_at": "2026-03-01T18:52:21+00:00",
        "scan_verified": false
      }
    },
    "review::.::holistic::error_consistency::GS_ERR_001::d439d18b": {
      "id": "review::.::holistic::error_consistency::GS_ERR_001::d439d18b",
      "detector": "review",
      "file": ".",
      "tier": 3,
      "confidence": "high",
      "summary": "`KillContainerUsingPort` can report success when container stop fails, masking port-reclaim failures during startup.",
      "detail": {
        "holistic": true,
        "dimension": "error_consistency",
        "related_files": [
          "goseg/docker/network/network.go",
          "goseg/docker/lifecycle/lifecycle.go"
        ],
        "evidence": [
          "`KillContainerUsingPort` iterates matching containers and on `cli.ContainerStop` error logs only (`zap.L().Error`) and does not return that error.",
          "In the same function, it returns `nil` immediately after attempting stop on first match even if stop failed.",
          "`lifecycle.Initialize` calls `network.KillContainerUsingPort(80)` and only logs the error, so upstream startup is not blocked by failed port cleanup."
        ],
        "suggestion": "Change `KillContainerUsingPort` to only return nil when all required teardown steps succeed; return the stop error when a stop attempt fails and let callers decide severity. In `lifecycle.Initialize`, fail hard or route to explicit degraded-mode recovery when port cleanup fails.",
        "reasoning": ""
      },
      "status": "fixed",
      "note": "KillContainerUsingPort now propagates container stop errors to callers rather than ignoring them, preventing false-success reporting when port cleanup fails.",
      "first_seen": "2026-03-01T18:49:27+00:00",
      "last_seen": "2026-03-01T18:49:27+00:00",
      "resolved_at": "2026-03-01T18:52:23+00:00",
      "reopen_count": 0,
      "lang": "go",
      "suppressed": false,
      "suppressed_at": null,
      "suppression_pattern": null,
      "resolution_attestation": {
        "kind": "manual",
        "text": "I have actually updated goseg/docker/network/network.go to return container-stop failures from KillContainerUsingPort instead of swallowing them and returning success. This ensures startup teardown errors from lifecycle.Initialize can be handled consistently by callers. I am not gaming the score by resolving without fixing.",
        "attested_at": "2026-03-01T18:52:23+00:00",
        "scan_verified": false
      }
    },
    "review::.::holistic::error_consistency::GS_ERR_002::62e73379": {
      "id": "review::.::holistic::error_consistency::GS_ERR_002::62e73379",
      "detector": "review",
      "file": ".",
      "tier": 3,
      "confidence": "medium",
      "summary": "Top-level startup boundary treats subsystem initialization errors inconsistently, enabling partially initialized runtime without clear failure contract.",
      "detail": {
        "holistic": true,
        "dimension": "error_consistency",
        "related_files": [
          "goseg/main.go",
          "goseg/broadcast/broadcast.go"
        ],
        "evidence": [
          "`main.go` exits on `config.Initialize()` error but only logs errors for many later initializers and continues startup.",
          "`broadcast.Initialize()` can return bootstrap errors (`unable to initialize broadcast state`) while `main.go` does not propagate these as startup failures.",
          "`main.go` starts the server and long-running routines even after non-fatal-logged failures in multiple dependencies, increasing risk of nil/partial state behavior at runtime."
        ],
        "suggestion": "Introduce a consistent init contract (fatal vs recoverable) and enforce it at the main boundary. Return/aggregate initialization errors from each subsystem, and decide deterministic policy: either stop startup on mandatory init failures or record state and suppress route/routine registration until dependency checks pass.",
        "reasoning": ""
      },
      "status": "open",
      "note": null,
      "first_seen": "2026-03-01T18:49:27+00:00",
      "last_seen": "2026-03-01T18:49:27+00:00",
      "resolved_at": null,
      "reopen_count": 0,
      "lang": "go",
      "suppressed": false,
      "suppressed_at": null,
      "suppression_pattern": null
    }
